Theoretical Framework It is now widely accepted by sociologists that any social problem consists of
two elements: an objective condition and its constructed definition, The most ardent objectivists wiII admit that claims making contributes to the process in which a condition comes to be deftned as problematic and worthy of intervention. Likewise, the vast majority of social constructionists wiII admit that there is usually an observable basis for the claims of activists. What they disagree about is the relative importance of conditions and defmitions. Siding with the constructionists, we select the pluralistically-grounded model developed by Mauss (1975,1984,1989) to analyze the 1986 War on Drugs.
The most recent major contributions to the social constructionist perspective in addition to Mauss were made by Spector and Kitsuse (1973, 1977). While there are several differences between their approaches, they share a complete reliance on deftnitions rather than conditions. Mauss's approach differs from that of Spector and Kitsuse in that he integrates social movement literature into the study of social problems. His approach emphasizes the similarity between social problems and social movements. He argues that social problems are a special kind of movement that begin at the grass-roots level (Mauss 1975, 1984, 1989). For the present purposes, his model is the most relevant because it is based on an ideology of how social problems should arise in a democratic society originating at the popular level and growing to later influence governmental representatives and public policy. While this position has been conftrmed for the construction of a number of social problems, we argue that a condition can come to be deftned as problematic by powerful interests without the prior existence of a social movement.
Following an established tradition in the study of social movements, Mauss (1975) argued that social problems go through five stages: incipiency, coalescence, institutionalization, fragmentation and demise.
Incipiency
In this stage there is neither strong leadership nor an organized membership in the emerging movement. Members of a public are concerned with the issue at this stage, but no formal organizations exist to champion the cause or to espouse the ideals of the movement.
Coalescence
Mauss (1975:62) stated that in this stage "formal and informal organizations develop out of segments of the sympathetic public that have become the most

