aroused by perceived threats to the preservation or realization of their interests."
Institutionalization This stage is reached "when the government and other traditional
institutions take official notice of a problem or movement and work out a series of standard coping mechanisms to manage it" (Mauss 1975:63). Institutionalization is marked by a societal-wide organization of groups involved in the problem, lobbying efforts, and attention in the mass media. This is when the movement reaches its peak of success and influence. Government actions adopt movement-inspired programs to deal with the problem.
Fragmentation Fragmentation occurs primarily in response to co-optation in the previous
stage. Many members of the movement perceive their goals to be achieved in the institutionalization stage with the passage of programs supported by the activists to resolve the problem.
Demise Demise represents the final stage. With claims makers losing interest in the
issue following co-optive legislation and programs, and since many of the leaders have been "brought off" by the establishment, only a dedicated core of true believers is left to carry on the fight.
In this article we examine the extent to which the recently rediscovered drug abuse problem conforms to this pluralistically-based model. In the next section, we present data indicating the absence of a rise in the overall consumption of illicit drugs during recent years.2 Following that section, we trace public opinion surrounding the issue and the construction of the social problem. Factors serving to precipitate the "creation" of the drug problem are then discussed. In a concluding section we discuss the implications of the findings for social problems theory.
Trends in illicit Drug Use The 1986 War on Drugs seems to be based on the assumption of a sizeable
increase in the use/abuse of illicit drugs in recent years. In order to evaluate this assumption, we turn to national self-reports of drug use? The most comprehensive of the national surveys is produced by the National Institute on Drug Abuse (NIDA). This self-report study questions nationally representative samples of persons 12 years of age and older. Data are available from this source for selected years,"
Regarding marijuana - the most commonly used illicit drug - the NIDA data show that lifetime, annual and monthly prevalence peaked in 1979for youth (ages 12-17) and young adults (ages 18-25). Older adults (age 26 and older)

