political issues related to drug use/abuse arose that only a few years earlier were not widely accepted, and some of which would have almost certainly engendered strong opposition. Driving under the influence of alcohol became a major issue beginning in 1982and crested in 1984. Politicians competed with each other to be seen as the toughest on drunk drivers. Also, a concerted effort was initiated to raise the drinking age to 21 in all states, ostensibly in an attempt to reduce drunk driving. Drug testing also emerged as a social issue with the 1986War on Drugs (ef.,Trebach 1987;Gerber et al.l990). Capital punishment for specified drug-related crimes and elimination of the exclusionary rule under certain circumstances were also being discussed as part of the arsenal in the war on drugs. Somewhat further removed from drugs, the rights of individuals, defended by conservatives on certain issues, were being challenged by the increasing use of AIDS testing and lie detectors in a variety of settings. Thus, it was in this general setting of conservatism that drugs could again emerge as a leading social problem.
A second triggering factor was the anti-drug campaign of Nancy Reagan. When Ronald Reagan was elected President in 1980, Nancy Reagan was portrayed by the media as a cold and insensitive person whose chief concern seemed to be her wardrobe. Because of this portrayal she sought to change her public image. The primary issue she chose to focus on was drug abuse, although she apparently had considered other campaigns (Beck 1981). While her work with drugs may have been initially little more than "a splendid public relations vehicle for the Reagan White House" (Trebach 1987:121), it received extensive media coverage and provided an underpinning for the creation of the drug problem in 1986.
The news media can playa crucial role in shaping images of social issues (Schneider 1985). In an effort to gauge the influence of the print media as a precipitating factor in the construction of the drug problem, we counted citations in The Readers' Guide to Periodical Literature. Table 2 presents the number of articles on illicit drugs that were published between 1975 and 1986.7 The data show that there was relatively little coverage of drug use/abuse from 1975 to 1977. A review of the articles published during these years indicates that use of marijuana received the most coverage, while heroin and cocaine were not major concerns.
There was a significant increase in the coverage of illicit drugs in the print media starting in 1978 and peaking in 1979 and 1980. Marijuana was still the drug receiving most of the press coverage. A number of developments occurred, however, that changed the focus of attention. A number of well-known individuals were either arrested for possession or sale of drugs, or received attention in conjunction with illicit drugs. Hamilton Jordan, a former member of the Carter administration, was arrested on cocaine charges in 1979. Paul McCartney's marijuana-related arrest in Japan received widespread media coverage in the United States in 1980. That same year, Richard Pryor

