drug abuse pre se as the most important problem in the nation, the public considered drug use by students to be the most important problem facing the public schools.
Publicity surrounding crack and the cocaine-related deaths of Len Bias and Don Rogers spurred renewed interest in the drug issue during mid-May and June 1986. Evidence of the coalescence stage is found at this time in the emergence of interest group efforts to publicize and combat crack use in New York City. However, the coalescence stage did not fully develop as proposed by Mauss (1975). The groups that were forming and responding to the crack "epidemic" remained localized and rather ineffectual. Instead of a wave of new grass-roots organizations or existing voluntary associations championing the problem, politicians gathered around the issue only months before the 1986 Congressional elections. A new war on drugs was their answer to a lackluster campaign season. Proposals for tax reform and the administration's attack on pornography were attracting little voter support. Furthermore, President Reagan was "trapped in a thicket of thorny problems, not the least of which were budget and trade deficits and sanctions against South Africa" (U.S. News and World Report1986b:28). Drugs were a safe issue for incumbent politicians who wanted to take the "moral high road" on an issue (see Gerber et al, 1990; Ben-Yehuda 1986; Nelson 1984; Newsweek 1986; U.S. News and World Report 1986a, 1986b).
The development of this social problem jumped from the beginnings of a coalescence stage directly into an early part of what Mauss labeled the institutionalization stage. This occurred first when Congressional Democrats announced on July23 a bipartisan effort to pass legislation to combat drug abuse and proposed an anti-drug bill on August 1. The construction of a drug problem was reaffirmed when President Reagan announced his anti-drug effort a few days later. This process continued in mid-September when the House overwhelmingly passed its version of the anti-drug bill, and President and Mrs. Reagan made their joint televised address to the nation. Formal creation of the problem and policy formation culminated in mid-October when the drug bill was passed and signed into law by the President, only two weeks before the elections.
The history of this social problem further deviated from the Mauss model at this point in its development. The politicians who had "created" the problem needed public support for their positions. All of the actions described above thus served two functions: on one hand they represented something similar to the institutionalization stage of Mauss's model, but on the other they served as mechanisms to attract public support. While the Mauss model predicts the intensification of public concern first (coalescence), which is then followed by official recognition, we argue that this social problem was institutionalized before public concern went beyond early coalescence. Support for this

