Creation and Policy Formation
Politicians or a government agency assert the existence of an undesirable condition, advocate the legitimacy of their claims, and propose a remedy for the "problem" in an effort to advance their own interests (Randall and Short 1983).

Legitimation By publicizing their claims, politicians or other state officials will attempt to
generate public support for their position. Furthermore, these state officials need to establish the legitimacy of their "mandate regarding both claims and solutions which are favorable" to their interests (Randall and Short 1983:421).
A short-lived fragmentation of the drug problem followed the legitimation stage. With the elections concluded and a major federal bill in effect, most politicians returned to business-as-usual. The drug problem continued to be important to the public throughout 1987 and early 1988, but slipped out of the
politiciallimelight (see 17,e Gallup RepOrl1987).
With the advent of the presidential campaign season during the spring of 1988, political claims makers revived the drug issue. Opinion polls indicated that drugs were an important issue in the presidential election (see The
Spokesman Review 1988; The Chronicle of Higher Education 1988; Newsweek
1988). The drug issue has been firmly constructed in the public eye. While the demise of the drug "problem" cannot be predicted, researchers will continue to monitor claims-making activities and policy outcomes of this most recent war
on drugs.

